10 mission is focused on Juneteenth Day education, unity and diversity; (3) one
11 member who represents a professional association representing African-American
12 businesses; (4) one member who represents an African-American cultural
13 awareness advocacy group; (5) one member who represents an educational
14 advocacy group with a statewide presence; and (6) one member who represents a
15 museum or cultural history organization in this State. To the extent that funding is
16 available, section 1.6 requires the Department to provide administrative support to
17 the Commission.
18 Section 1.7 of this bill requires the Commission to: (1) create and distribute
19 written, electronic or printed materials to educate the public on the history and
20 meaning of Juneteenth Day in the State of Nevada and the United States; (2)
21 develop strategies with businesses, nonprofit organizations and community groups
22 to support education on the significance of Juneteenth Day; (3) support the efforts
23 of businesses, community groups and local governments to establish events and
24 programs relating to Juneteenth Day throughout the State; and (4) support programs
25 in the arts to celebrate Juneteenth Day.
26 Section 1.8 of this bill creates the Juneteenth Educational and Economic Fund
27 for the support of the Commission.
28 Sections 1.2-1.5 of this bill define certain terms relating to the Commission.
29 Existing law creates the Joint Interim Standing Committee on Education and
30 authorizes the Committee to: (1) evaluate, review and comment upon issues related
31 to education in this State; (2) conduct investigations and hold hearings in
32 connection with such duties; and (3) make recommendations to the Legislature
33 relating to the improvement of public education. (NRS 218E.320, 218E.615)
34 Existing law requires the Joint Interim Standing Committee on Education to
35 prepare and submit to the Legislature a comprehensive report of its activities in the
36 interim and its findings and any recommendations for proposed legislation. (NRS
37 218E.330) Section 1.9 of this bill creates the Subcommittee to Study and Develop
38 Policy Recommendations for African-Americans of the Joint Interim Standing
39 Committee on Education to conduct the study set forth in section 2 of this bill
40 during the 2025-2026 interim. Section 1.9 prescribes the membership and officers
41 of the Subcommittee and the compensation of the members. Section 1.9 also
42 provides for the filling of vacancies and requirements for meetings.
43 Section 2 requires the Subcommittee to: (1) study certain matters relating to
44 historical discrimination in this State and the related economic effects of the
45 discrimination to present day society in this State; and (2) present its findings and
46 make recommendations relating to its findings to the Joint Interim Standing
47 Committee on Education, for inclusion in its 2026-2026 interim report, for methods
48 to educate the general public about the findings and recommendations of the
49 Subcommittee, advancement of racial healing, understanding and transformation
50 and the form and scope of rehabilitation or restitution to the descendants of
51 formerly enslaved Africans, if warranted, based on the findings of the
52 Subcommittee. Section 2 authorizes the Subcommittee to collaborate and consult
53 with and invite participation by historians, scholars and other interested parties and
54 requires state agencies to provide any information requested by the Subcommittee
55 relating to its duties. Section 2 also authorizes the Subcommittee to: (1) request
56 assistance from the Division of State Library, Archives and Public Records of the
57 Department of Administration, which is required to provide assistance to the extent
58 that resources are available; and (2) direct the Legislative Counsel Bureau to assist
59 in its research investigations, review and analysis.
60 Section 2 further authorizes the Subcommittee to apply for and accept certain
61 funds for the Subcommittee in carrying out its duties.
